article.description: DeWanna Bonner scored 25 points and Auburn beat Mississippi State 63-58 on Sunday, giving the Tigers 25 wins for the first time since 1992-93.
article.headline: Bonner's 25 help Auburn to first since 25-win season since '92-93
article.linkText: Bonner's 25 help Auburn to rare 25-win season
article.story:
STARKVILLE, Miss. -- Less than 3 minutes after crashing to the floor with tears in her eyes after an elbow to the head, DeWanna Bonner ran down the court with her hands in the air.

Auburn's do-everything senior had 25 points and 10 rebounds for her 38th career double-double, leading the Tigers (No. 4 ESPN/USA Today, No. 5 AP)
 to a 63-58 win over Mississippi State on Sunday.

Bonner scored eight straight points midway through the second half to keep Auburn in it, then led the Tigers (25-1, 10-1 Southeastern Conference) to the victory. She returned after taking an accidental blow to the head during a battle for a rebound and turned a steal into a fast-break layup.

The Tigers reached 25 wins for the first time since 1992-93.

"I knew I had to stay strong for the team," Bonner said. "My adrenaline carried me through. When you've got an injury like that, you just try to ignore it till the end of the game."

Bonner started slowly, but used her long, lean frame to create shots for herself in transition and cruise the paint for foul shots. She hit 11-for-12 from the line, including two key free throws as Auburn pulled away in the final minute.

"She's 6-4 and has guard skills," Auburn coach Nell Fortner said. "She can play any position on the floor and defend any position. That's what makes her so valuable."

The Tigers also got 18 points from Whitney Boddie, who hurt the Bulldogs (19-7, 6-5) with mid-range jump shots, and 13 from Sherrell Hobbs.

Alexis Rack led Mississippi State with 15 points and six assists, and Robin Porter had 13, including a layup on a pass from Rack that put the Bulldogs ahead 53-52 with 5:37 left.

Mississippi State double-teamed Bonner when she was under the basket and kept Auburn off balance with a man-to-man defense that put it in a position to win. The Tigers were first in the SEC and third in the nation with a 48 percent shooting percentage, but the Bulldogs held them five points below their average and scored 15 points off 17 turnovers.

"That was one of the best man defenses I've seen played this season," Bonner said.

She got off to a slow start thanks to the pressure and never really got used to it even as she began to hit shots in the second half.

"Once you got past one there was someone waiting to slap the ball," said Bonner, who is 76 points shy of breaking the school scoring record.

The Bulldogs missed eight of their final 10 shots, including three layups, and turned the ball over twice with the game on the line.

"We have to learn how to put it away and finish it right there," Mississippi State coach Sharon Fanning said. "There were a lot of great things we did. I am not into moral victories because I expect this team to win."

Auburn has won five straight since its 67-58 loss to Georgia on Jan. 29. Fortner said she hopes her team can learn something from Mississippi State's defense as the postseason approaches.

"I want to go look back on the film and see how they did it," Fortner said. "I want to figure out how to get my team to play like that because that was some really good defense.

"I'm just happy to get out of here with a win."
